## Changes

### 1. Group assistant messages under a single mascot
**Files:** `AssistantMessage.tsx`, `ActivityBlockView.tsx`

- When `showAvatar` is false, render a 36px-wide empty spacer div instead of the mascot (keeps bubble alignment)
- In `ActivityBlockView`, pass `showAvatar={idx === 0}` so only the first message in a block gets the mascot
- Wrap the assistant block messages in `<div className="space-y-1.5">` for tighter internal spacing

### 2. Make building blocks visible
**File:** `BuildingBlock.tsx`

Here is a thorough breakdown of the full project management data flow.

---

## Project Management System — Full Data Flow

---

### 1. Electron Store (`electron/project-store.mjs`)

The persistence layer is an `electron-store` instance named `cc4d-projects`. It stores two top-level keys:

- `projects` — array of `ProjectMeta` objects
- `activeProjectId` — string or null

**Schema fields per project:**
`id`, `name`, `displayName`, `path`, `createdAt`, `lastOpenedAt`, `sessionId`, `locale`, `vibe`, `audience`, `priority`, `designRef`, `liveUrl`, `githubUrl`

**Exported functions:**
```js
getProjects()           // returns all projects array
getProject(id)          // returns single project by id
addProject(meta)        // push + set activeProjectId
updateProject(id, upd)  // patch project in array
removeProject(id)       // filter out project, clears activeProjectId if matched
getActiveProject()      // lookup by stored activeProjectId
setActiveProjectId(id)  // sets active id directly
```

`removeProject` is fully implemented in the store but — **critically — there is no IPC handler registered for it**. It exists only in the store module and in unit tests. It is never exposed to the renderer.

---

### 2. IPC Handlers (`electron/ipc-handlers.js`)

Registered project-related channels:

| IPC channel | What it does |
|---|---|
| `project:create` | Creates folder, git init, copies skill files, calls `addProject`, returns `ProjectMeta` |
| `project:list` | Returns all projects sorted by `lastOpenedAt` descending |
| `project:switch` | Validates path exists, updates `lastOpenedAt`, sets `activeProjectId`, returns updated meta |
| `project:update` | Calls `updateProject(id, updates)` — patches any field |
| `project:get-active` | Returns `getActiveProject()` |
| `project:finalize-preferences` | Re-writes CLAUDE.md, updates progress JSON, persists vibe/audience/priority/designRef |

**There is no `project:delete` or `project:remove` handler.** The `removeProject` store function is never wired to IPC.

---

### 3. Preload Bridge (`electron/preload.js`)

Exposes `window.electronAPI` to the renderer via `contextBridge`. Project-related methods:

```js
window.electronAPI.createProject(idea, locale)     // → project:create
window.electronAPI.listProjects()                  // → project:list
```

- If `deleteFiles` is true, uses `fs.rm(project.path, { recursive: true, force: true })` to delete the folder
- Logs the action
- Returns `{ success: true }` or throws

### 2. Preload bridge
**File:** `electron/preload.js`

Add:
```js
deleteProject: (id, deleteFiles) =>
  ipcRenderer.invoke("project:delete", { id, deleteFiles }),
```

### 3. TypeScript types
**File:** `src/types/electron-api.d.ts`

```ts
deleteProject: (id: string, deleteFiles: boolean) => Promise<{ success: boolean }>;
```

- `deleteCancel` — "Cancel" / "ביטול"

**File:** `src/app/welcome/page.tsx`

# Fix Chat UX Issues

## Context
The desktop app's chat UI has several visual problems visible in the screenshot: repeated mascot avatars on every assistant message, building blocks that are nearly invisible against the yellow background, an overwhelming all-yellow color scheme, and the PlanningHeader taking up too much space once conversation starts.

## Changes

### 1. Group assistant messages under a single mascot
**Files:** `AssistantMessage.tsx`, `ActivityBlockView.tsx`

- Add `showAvatar?: boolean` prop to `AssistantMessage` (default `true`)
- When `showAvatar` is false, render a 36px-wide empty spacer div instead of the mascot (keeps bubble alignment)
- In `ActivityBlockView`, pass `showAvatar={idx === 0}` so only the first message in a block gets the mascot
- Wrap the assistant block messages in `<div className="space-y-1.5">` for tighter internal spacing

### 2. Make building blocks visible
**File:** `BuildingBlock.tsx`

- Container: `bg-dummy-black/5` → `bg-dummy-white/60 backdrop-blur-sm`
- Left border: `border-dummy-black/20` → `border-dummy-black/40`
- Summary text: `text-dummy-black/70` → `text-dummy-black/80`
- Icons: `text-dummy-black/50` → `text-dummy-black/60`

### 3. Improve chat area contrast
**Files:** `build/page.tsx`, `LiveActivityBar.tsx`

- Chat area bg: `bg-dummy-yellow-bright/30` → `bg-dummy-yellow/15` (lighter cream)
- LiveActivityBar: `bg-dummy-yellow-bright/40` → `bg-dummy-white/70` (frosted white strip)

### 4. Compact PlanningHeader after conversation starts
**File:** `PlanningHeader.tsx`

- Track `messages.length` from the store
- When `messageCount > 2`: switch to compact horizontal layout (32px mascot, single-line title, no subtitle) — reclaims ~150px of vertical space
- Use Framer Motion `layout` prop for smooth transition

## Verification
- Run `cd desktop && npm run dev`
- Start a new wizard session and verify: PlanningHeader shrinks after first exchange
- Send multiple messages and verify: assistant messages share one mascot per block
- Check building blocks are clearly visible against the background
- Verify RTL layout still works correctly (mascot on right side, text aligned properly)

The desktop app's chat UI has several visual problems visible in the screenshot: repeated mascot avatars on every assistant message, building blocks that are nearly invisible against the yellow background, an overwhelming all-yellow color scheme, and the PlanningHeader taking up too much space once conversation starts.

## Changes

### 1. Group assistant messages under a single mascot
**Files:** `AssistantMessage.tsx`, `ActivityBlockView.tsx`

- Add `showAvatar?: boolean` prop to `AssistantMessage` (default `true`)
- When `showAvatar` is false, render a 36px-wide empty spacer div instead of the mascot (keeps bubble alignment)
- In `ActivityBlockView`, pass `showAvatar={idx === 0}` so only the first message in a block gets the mascot
- Wrap the assistant block messages in `<div className="space-y-1.5">` for tighter internal spacing

### 2. Make building blocks visible
**File:** `BuildingBlock.tsx`

- Container: `bg-dummy-black/5` → `bg-dummy-white/60 backdrop-blur-sm`
- Left border: `border-dummy-black/20` → `border-dummy-black/40`
- Summary text: `text-dummy-black/70` → `text-dummy-black/80`
- Icons: `text-dummy-black/50` → `text-dummy-black/60`

### 3. Improve chat area contrast
**Files:** `build/page.tsx`, `LiveActivityBar.tsx`

- Chat area bg: `bg-dummy-yellow-bright/30` → `bg-dummy-yellow/15` (lighter cream)
- LiveActivityBar: `bg-dummy-yellow-bright/40` → `bg-dummy-white/70` (frosted white strip)

### 4. Compact PlanningHeader after conversation starts
**File:** `PlanningHeader.tsx`

- Track `messages.length` from the store
- When `messageCount > 2`: switch to compact horizontal layout (32px mascot, single-line title, no subtitle) — reclaims ~150px of vertical space
- Use Framer Motion `layout` prop for smooth transition

## Verification
- Run `cd desktop && npm run dev`
- Start a new wizard session and verify: PlanningHeader shrinks after first exchange
- Send multiple messages and verify: assistant messages share one mascot per block
- Check building blocks are clearly visible against the background
- Verify RTL layout still works correctly (mascot on right side, text aligned properly)

# Delete Projects Feature

## Context
The welcome page lists projects but has no way to remove them. Users accumulate test projects and want to clean up. The `removeProject()` function already exists in `electron/project-store.mjs` but is never wired to IPC or exposed to the renderer.

## Changes

### 1. IPC handler — `project:delete`
**File:** `electron/ipc-handlers.js`

Add a new `project:delete` handler that:
- Looks up the project by id to get its `path`
- Calls `projectStore.removeProject(id)` to remove from electron-store
- If `deleteFiles` is true, uses `fs.rm(project.path, { recursive: true, force: true })` to delete the folder
- Logs the action
- Returns `{ success: true }` or throws

### 2. Preload bridge
**File:** `electron/preload.js`

Add `deleteProject` method that invokes `project:delete`.

### 3. TypeScript types
**File:** `src/types/electron-api.d.ts`

Add `deleteProject: (id: string, deleteFiles: boolean) => Promise<{ success: boolean }>` to the interface.

### 4. i18n strings
**Files:** `messages/he.json`, `messages/en.json`

Add under `"Welcome"`:
- `deleteProject`, `deleteConfirmTitle`, `deleteConfirmMessage`
- `deleteKeepFiles`, `deleteAndRemoveFiles`, `deleteCancel`

### 5. Delete button + confirmation modal on welcome page
**File:** `src/app/welcome/page.tsx`

- Add a `Trash2` icon button on each project card (visible on hover via group-hover)
- `e.stopPropagation()` to prevent card navigation
- Sets `deletingProject` state to show an inline confirmation modal
- Modal shows project name and three options:
  - "Just remove from list" → `deleteProject(id, false)`
  - "Also delete files from my computer" → `deleteProject(id, true)`
  - "Cancel"
- On confirm: call API, then filter the project from local `recentProjects` state
- Use `AnimatePresence` for smooth card removal animation

## Files Modified
1. `electron/ipc-handlers.js` — new `project:delete` IPC handler
2. `electron/preload.js` — expose `deleteProject`
3. `src/types/electron-api.d.ts` — type the new method
4. `messages/he.json` + `messages/en.json` — i18n strings
5. `src/app/welcome/page.tsx` — delete button + confirmation UI

## Verification
- `cd desktop && npm run dev`
- Open welcome page with existing projects
- Hover a project card → trash icon appears
- Click trash → confirmation modal appears
- Test "Just remove from list" → project disappears, files remain on disk
- Test "Also delete files" → project disappears, folder deleted
- Test cancel → nothing happens
- Verify RTL layout (Hebrew)
- Build check: `npx next build`
